President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate Steven Christopher Koutsis as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the Republic of Chad. Koutsis is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and currently serves as Charge d'Affaires of the United States Embassy in Khartoum, Sudan. He has held various positions in the State Department, including Director of the Office of the Special Envoy for Sudan and South Sudan, Deputy Chief of Mission in Burkina Faso, and Deputy Director in the Office of Central African Affairs. Koutsis has a B.A. from Boston University and has received the Department of Army Superior Civilian Service Award for his service in Iraq. He speaks French and Arabic.

President Trump has also announced his intent to appoint Robert A. Ingram, Edith Peterson Mitchell, and John P. Williams as members of the President's Cancer Panel. Ingram, from North Carolina, will serve for the remainder of a three-year term expiring in 2022. Mitchell, from Tennessee, will serve for the remainder of a three-year term expiring in 2020. Williams, from Virginia, will serve for the remainder of a three-year term expiring in 2021 and will be designated Chairman for a one-year term.